        yearLabel: "1492 CE",
        description: "In August 1492, Christopher Columbus departed the port of Palos de la Frontera in southern Spain with three small ships — the Niña, the Pinta, and the Santa María — on a voyage financed by Queen Isabella I and King Ferdinand II of Spain. Columbus, a Genoese navigator who had spent years lobbying European courts, believed he could reach the lucrative spice markets of Asia by sailing westward across the Atlantic Ocean, a route no European had successfully attempted. After five weeks at sea, during which his increasingly restless crew threatened mutiny, land was sighted on October 12, 1492.\n\nColumbus made landfall on an island in the Bahamas that the indigenous Taíno people called Guanahani, which he renamed San Salvador. Convinced he had reached the outer islands of Asia — specifically the Indies — Columbus called the native inhabitants 'Indians,' a misnomer that persisted for centuries. Over the next several months, he explored the coasts of Cuba and Hispaniola (modern-day Haiti and the Dominican Republic), establishing a small settlement called La Navidad from the timbers of the wrecked Santa María. He encountered the Taíno and Arawak peoples, noting their hospitality while simultaneously assessing their potential for conversion to Christianity and forced labor.\n\nThe consequences of Columbus's voyages were staggering in their scope and devastation. His four transatlantic expeditions between 1492 and 1504 initiated what historians call the Columbian Exchange — the most significant ecological event since the extinction of the dinosaurs. From the Americas to Europe flowed potatoes, tomatoes, maize, tobacco, chocolate, and rubber, crops that would transform European agriculture and cuisine. From Europe to the Americas came wheat, horses, cattle, and sugar cane, but also smallpox, measles, influenza, and typhus — diseases against which indigenous populations had no immunity.\n\nThe demographic catastrophe that followed was unprecedented. Within a century of contact, an estimated 90 percent of the indigenous population of the Americas — perhaps 50 to 60 million people — had perished, primarily from epidemic disease. The Taíno people Columbus first encountered were virtually extinct within fifty years. This population collapse created a labor vacuum that European colonizers filled through the transatlantic slave trade, forcibly transporting an estimated 12.5 million Africans to the Americas over the following four centuries.\n\nColumbus himself governed Hispaniola with brutal incompetence, enslaving indigenous people and imposing tribute systems so harsh that the Spanish crown eventually stripped him of his titles and had him returned to Spain in chains. He died in 1506, still insisting he had reached Asia. His legacy remains deeply contested: celebrated for centuries as a heroic explorer who 'discovered' the New World, he is now more accurately understood as the initiator of European colonialism in the Americas, a process that brought immense wealth to Europe at an incalculable cost in human suffering.",
