        id: "em5",
        title: "Martin Luther Sparks the Protestant Reformation",
        year: 1517,
        yearLabel: "1517 CE",
        description: "On October 31, 1517, Martin Luther, an Augustinian monk and theology professor at the University of Wittenberg in Saxony, posted his Ninety-Five Theses on the door of the Castle Church — a conventional academic gesture inviting scholarly debate. The document challenged the Catholic Church's sale of indulgences, certificates that promised the purchaser or their deceased loved ones reduced time in purgatory. What began as a theological dispute within the Church escalated into the most profound religious revolution in Western history, permanently fracturing the unity of Western Christendom.\n\nThe immediate catalyst was the preaching of Johann Tetzel, a Dominican friar authorized by Pope Leo X to sell indulgences to finance the construction of St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. Tetzel's salesmanship was aggressive and theologically dubious — he reportedly told buyers that 'as soon as the coin in the coffer rings, the soul from purgatory springs.' Luther's theses attacked the theological foundations of indulgences, arguing that salvation came through faith alone (sola fide) and that the pope had no authority over purgatory. More fundamentally, Luther asserted that Scripture alone (sola scriptura), not Church tradition or papal authority, was the ultimate source of religious truth.\n\nThe printing press, invented by Johannes Gutenberg barely sixty years earlier, transformed what might have remained a local academic quarrel into a continental revolution. Luther's theses were translated from Latin into German and reprinted in every major city in the Holy Roman Empire within weeks. His subsequent writings — including 'To the Christian Nobility of the German Nation,' 'On the Babylonian Captivity of the Church,' and 'On the Freedom of a Christian' — were produced in editions of thousands, making Luther the first best-selling author in the age of print.\n\nWhen summoned to recant before the Imperial Diet at Worms in 1521, Luther reportedly declared, 'Here I stand. I can do no other. God help me.' Emperor Charles V placed Luther under the ban of the Empire, but Frederick the Wise of Saxony sheltered him at the Wartburg Castle, where Luther translated the New Testament into vigorous, accessible German — a work that helped standardize the German language much as the King James Bible later shaped English.\n\nThe Reformation unleashed forces far beyond Luther's control or intention. Radical reformers like Thomas Müntzer inspired the German Peasants' War of 1524-25, which Luther denounced, siding with the princes who crushed the revolt with horrific violence. Ulrich Zwingli in Zurich, John Calvin in Geneva, and John Knox in Scotland developed their own reformed theologies, each differing from Luther's and from each other. Henry VIII's break with Rome in 1534 — motivated more by his desire for a male heir than by theology — created the Church of England. The Catholic Church responded with the Counter-Reformation, the Council of Trent, and the Society of Jesus (Jesuits), reclaiming some lost ground while hardening doctrinal positions.\n\nThe religious divisions spawned over a century of devastating warfare — the French Wars of Religion, the Dutch Revolt, the Thirty Years' War — that killed millions and redrew the political map of Europe. Yet the Reformation also planted seeds of modern pluralism, the idea that a society could contain multiple faiths, and of individual conscience as a legitimate basis for dissent against established authority.",
