        id: "em6",
        title: "Fall of the Aztec Empire",
        year: 1521,
        yearLabel: "1521 CE",
        description: "The fall of the Aztec Empire in 1521 was one of the most dramatic and consequential conquests in world history — the destruction of a sophisticated civilization of millions by a few hundred Spanish adventurers aided by indigenous allies, European diseases, and superior military technology. The conquest reshaped the demographics, culture, and ecology of an entire continent and established the template for European colonialism in the Americas.\n\nHernán Cortés landed on the Gulf Coast of Mexico in February 1519 with approximately 600 soldiers, 16 horses, and a few small cannons. He was defying the authority of the governor of Cuba, who had authorized only a trading expedition, not a conquest. Cortés burned his ships — eliminating any possibility of retreat — and marched inland toward Tenochtitlan, the Aztec capital. Along the way, he formed crucial alliances with indigenous peoples who resented Aztec domination, particularly the Tlaxcalans, who provided thousands of warriors.\n\nTenochtitlan, built on an island in Lake Texcoco at the site of modern Mexico City, was one of the largest and most magnificent cities in the world, with an estimated population of 200,000 to 300,000 — larger than any city in contemporary Europe except perhaps Constantinople. The Aztec emperor Montezuma II received Cortés with elaborate ceremony in November 1519, possibly believing the Spaniards were connected to the god Quetzalcoatl, though this interpretation is debated by modern scholars. Cortés repaid this hospitality by taking Montezuma hostage.\n\nThe situation deteriorated rapidly. In June 1520, during Cortés's temporary absence, his lieutenant Pedro de Alvarado massacred Aztec nobles during a religious festival, provoking a furious uprising. Montezuma was killed — either stoned by his own people while attempting to calm them, or murdered by the Spanish. Cortés and his forces were driven from the city on La Noche Triste (the Night of Sorrows), losing hundreds of Spanish soldiers and thousands of Tlaxcalan allies as they fought their way across the causeways.\n\nCortés regrouped, built brigantines to control the lake, and besieged Tenochtitlan for 80 days beginning in May 1521. The city's defenders, now led by the young emperor Cuauhtémoc, fought with extraordinary tenacity, but smallpox — introduced by an infected member of an earlier Spanish expedition — was ravaging the population. When the city finally fell on August 13, 1521, it was a ruin. Cortés estimated that 100,000 people had died during the siege, and the stench of unburied dead was overwhelming. The Spanish demolished Tenochtitlan and built Mexico City on its foundations, using the stones of Aztec temples to construct Catholic churches.\n\nThe conquest inaugurated three centuries of Spanish colonial rule in Mexico and Central America. The indigenous population of central Mexico, estimated at 15 to 25 million in 1519, collapsed to approximately 1 million by 1600, primarily due to epidemic disease. The Aztec language (Nahuatl), religion, and political structures were systematically suppressed, though elements survived through syncretic blending with Spanish culture. The vast quantities of gold and silver extracted from Mexico and later Peru funded Spanish hegemony in Europe for the next century.",
