        id: "em8",
        title: "Conquest of the Inca Empire",
        year: 1533,
        yearLabel: "1533 CE",
        description: "The Spanish conquest of the Inca Empire, the largest empire in pre-Columbian America, was accomplished with breathtaking speed and ruthlessness by Francisco Pizarro and a tiny force of conquistadors who exploited civil war, disease, technological superiority, and sheer audacity to topple a civilization that controlled over 10 million people across 2,500 miles of the Andes Mountains.\n\nPizarro, an illiterate former swineherd from Extremadura, had spent years exploring the Pacific coast of South America before receiving royal authorization for a conquest expedition. He landed on the Peruvian coast in 1532 with approximately 168 soldiers, 27 horses, and a few small cannons. His timing was extraordinarily fortunate: the Inca Empire was convulsed by a civil war between two half-brothers, Atahualpa and Huáscar, both sons of the recently deceased emperor Huayna Capac, who had himself likely died of a European disease (possibly smallpox) that had spread south from Panama before any Spaniard set foot in Peru.\n\nAtahualpa, having won the civil war, was encamped with an army of 80,000 at the highland city of Cajamarca when Pizarro arrived in November 1532. The encounter that followed was one of the most audacious ambushes in military history. Pizarro invited Atahualpa to a meeting in the main square, where a Dominican friar presented the emperor with a Bible and demanded he accept Christianity and Spanish sovereignty. When Atahualpa, unfamiliar with books, held the Bible to his ear, heard nothing, and threw it to the ground, Pizarro gave the signal to attack.\n\nConcealed cavalry and infantry charged into the square, firing cannons and harquebuses into the packed mass of Atahualpa's unarmed retinue. In the chaos, perhaps 2,000 to 6,000 Incas were killed — the Spaniards suffered virtually no casualties. Pizarro personally seized Atahualpa, pulling him from his litter. The emperor, recognizing the Spaniards' hunger for gold, offered to fill a room 22 feet long, 17 feet wide, and 8 feet high with gold, and twice over with silver, in exchange for his freedom.\n\nOver the next several months, gold and silver poured into Cajamarca from across the empire — an estimated 13,000 pounds of gold and 26,000 pounds of silver, the largest ransom in history. Priceless artistic masterpieces — vessels, jewelry, sculptures, and temple ornaments representing centuries of Inca craftsmanship — were melted down into ingots. Despite receiving the ransom, Pizarro put Atahualpa on trial for polygamy, idolatry, and crimes against the Spanish crown, and had him executed by garrote on July 26, 1533.\n\nThe fall of the Inca Empire was not immediate. Pizarro installed puppet emperors, but Inca resistance continued for decades, most notably under Manco Inca, who besieged the Spanish in Cusco in 1536 with an army of 100,000. The last Inca stronghold at Vilcabamba was not conquered until 1572. Spanish colonial rule imposed the encomienda and mita systems of forced labor, particularly in the silver mines of Potosí, where millions of indigenous and African workers died over the following centuries. The silver extracted from Peru and Bolivia flooded the global economy, causing price revolutions in Europe and Asia.",
