        id: "em29",
        title: "Adam Smith Publishes The Wealth of Nations",
        year: 1776,
        yearLabel: "1776 CE",
        description: "On March 9, 1776 — just four months before the American Declaration of Independence — the Scottish moral philosopher Adam Smith published 'An Inquiry into the Nature and Causes of the Wealth of Nations,' a work that founded the modern discipline of economics and provided the intellectual framework for the market capitalism that would come to dominate the global economy. Like Newton's Principia for physics and Darwin's Origin for biology, Smith's work established the foundational paradigm of its field.\n\nSmith (1723-1790) was professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow and had already published a major philosophical work, 'The Theory of Moral Sentiments' (1759), which explored the role of sympathy and social approval in ethical behavior. The 'Wealth of Nations' was the product of over a decade of research and writing, including a period in France where Smith met the Physiocrats — economists who believed that agriculture was the sole source of wealth — and whose ideas he both absorbed and transcended.\n\nThe book's central argument was revolutionary in its implications: national wealth was not measured by gold and silver reserves (as mercantilist doctrine held) but by the total productive output of a nation's people. Smith argued that when individuals pursued their own self-interest in a competitive market, they were guided 'as if by an invisible hand' to promote the general welfare — the butcher, the brewer, and the baker provided dinner not from benevolence but from regard to their own interest. This insight — that private vice could produce public virtue — challenged centuries of moral and economic thinking.\n\nSmith identified the division of labor as the primary driver of productivity and economic growth. His famous example of the pin factory demonstrated how breaking a manufacturing process into specialized tasks could increase output thousands-fold. He argued that the extent of specialization was limited by the size of the market, providing a powerful argument for free trade and the removal of tariffs, monopolies, and other restrictions on commerce.\n\nHowever, Smith was far from the uncritical champion of unregulated capitalism that both his admirers and critics sometimes portray. He was deeply suspicious of merchants and manufacturers, warning that 'people of the same trade seldom meet together, even for merriment and diversion, but the conversation ends in a conspiracy against the public.' He advocated public education, regulation of banking, progressive taxation ('it is not very unreasonable that the rich should contribute to the public expense, not only in proportion to their revenue, but something more than in that proportion'), and government provision of infrastructure and defense.\n\nSmith's analysis of labor, wages, and profit exposed the class dynamics of capitalism with a clarity that would later inspire Karl Marx. His labor theory of value — the idea that the value of a commodity was determined by the labor required to produce it — became a cornerstone of classical economics and, through Ricardo, of Marxist economics. The 'Wealth of Nations' thus paradoxically provided intellectual ammunition for both the defenders and the critics of capitalism.\n\nThe book's influence was immense and immediate. William Pitt the Younger, Britain's prime minister, reportedly told Smith, 'We are all your scholars.' The 'Wealth of Nations' shaped British economic policy for a century, providing the intellectual justification for free trade, the repeal of the Corn Laws (1846), and the laissez-faire economics of the Victorian era. Its influence extends undiminished to the present: every debate about free markets versus regulation, globalization versus protectionism, and the proper role of government in the economy takes place in the intellectual framework that Adam Smith established.",
        category: "science",
        era: "early-modern",
        imageUrl: "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/AdamSmith.jpg/300px-AdamSmith.jpg",
        sourceLinks: [{ label: "Wikipedia", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wealth_of_Nations" }]
