        id: "em31",
        title: "Storming of the Bastille (French Revolution)",
        year: 1789,
        yearLabel: "1789 CE",
        description: "On July 14, 1789, a Parisian mob of approximately 1,000 people stormed the Bastille, a medieval fortress-prison in the eastern part of the city, in an event that became the defining symbol of the French Revolution and one of the most consequential days in modern history. The fall of the Bastille marked the violent beginning of a revolutionary process that would overthrow the French monarchy, transform European politics, inspire democratic movements worldwide, and unleash forces — including mass political violence and ideological warfare — that continue to shape the modern world.\n\nThe immediate crisis had been building for months. France was bankrupt, burdened by debts from the American Revolution and decades of royal extravagance. A catastrophic harvest in 1788 had driven bread prices to record highs, and Parisians were literally hungry. King Louis XVI, unable to raise taxes without consent, had been forced to convene the Estates-General — a representative assembly that had not met since 1614 — in May 1789. When the Third Estate (commoners) was denied equal representation, its delegates broke away and formed the National Assembly, swearing the Tennis Court Oath not to disband until France had a constitution.\n\nLouis XVI responded by concentrating troops around Paris, raising fears of a royal military coup. On July 11, he dismissed the popular finance minister Jacques Necker, provoking outrage. On July 12, crowds began arming themselves from arsenals across the city. On July 14, they marched on the Bastille, seeking the gunpowder stored within. The fortress was defended by a small garrison of 82 invalides (veteran soldiers) and 32 Swiss Guards under the command of Governor Bernard-René de Launay.\n\nAfter several hours of confused negotiation and sporadic fighting, the crowd broke through the outer defenses. De Launay surrendered on the promise of safe conduct, but the crowd — enraged by casualties (98 attackers had been killed) — seized him and hacked off his head with a pocketknife, parading it through the streets on a pike. The Bastille held only seven prisoners — four forgers, two lunatics, and a dissolute nobleman — but its symbolic significance was immense. It represented royal tyranny, arbitrary imprisonment (through lettres de cachet), and the power of the old regime over ordinary citizens.\n\nThe revolution that followed transformed France and Europe. The Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen, adopted on August 26, 1789, proclaimed that 'men are born and remain free and equal in rights' and that sovereignty resided in the nation rather than the king. The feudal system was abolished. The Church's property was nationalized. The monarchy was progressively stripped of power and finally abolished in September 1792.\n\nThe revolution also devoured its own children. The Reign of Terror (1793-94), directed by the Committee of Public Safety under Maximilien Robespierre, sent an estimated 16,000 to 40,000 people to the guillotine, including King Louis XVI, Queen Marie Antoinette, and eventually Robespierre himself. The Terror demonstrated that revolutionary idealism, unchecked by institutional constraints, could produce tyranny as brutal as any monarchy. The revolution ultimately culminated in the rise of Napoleon Bonaparte, who seized power in 1799 and crowned himself Emperor in 1804 — the revolution's great irony.\n\nJuly 14 became France's national day (Bastille Day), celebrated annually as the symbol of popular sovereignty and republican values. The revolution's legacy remains contested: to some it represents the birth of modern democracy and human rights; to others, the prototype of revolutionary violence and ideological extremism. Both interpretations contain truth.",
