        id: "em32",
        title: "Haitian Revolution",
        year: 1791,
        yearLabel: "1791 CE",
        description: "The Haitian Revolution (1791-1804) was the only successful large-scale slave revolt in history and one of the most radical revolutionary movements of the modern era. Enslaved Africans and their descendants in the French colony of Saint-Domingue rose up against their masters, defeated the armies of France, Spain, and Britain — the three most powerful military forces on Earth — and established Haiti as the first free Black republic and the second independent nation in the Western Hemisphere.\n\nSaint-Domingue was the wealthiest colony in the Caribbean and arguably the world, producing roughly 40 percent of Europe's sugar and 60 percent of its coffee. This extraordinary productivity was built on a system of slavery of almost unimaginable brutality. Approximately 500,000 enslaved Africans — two-thirds of whom had been born in Africa — labored on plantations where the average life expectancy after arrival was seven years. The planter class of roughly 40,000 whites maintained control through systematic terror: whippings, mutilations, burnings, and executions were routine.\n\nThe revolution began on the night of August 22, 1791, when enslaved people on the northern plain of Saint-Domingue launched a coordinated uprising, burning plantations and killing their masters. Within weeks, over 100,000 enslaved people had joined the revolt. The uprising was partly inspired by Vodou religious ceremonies — the ceremony at Bois Caïman, led by the priest Dutty Boukman, is traditionally regarded as the revolution's spiritual origin — and partly by the revolutionary ideals of liberty and equality emanating from France.\n\nThe dominant figure of the revolution was Toussaint Louverture, a formerly enslaved man of exceptional intelligence and military genius. Toussaint organized the rebel forces into a disciplined army, mastered guerrilla warfare, and navigated the extraordinarily complex political situation — playing France, Spain, and Britain against each other with Machiavellian skill. He allied with Spain against France (1793), then switched sides when France abolished slavery (1794), defeated a British expeditionary force of 20,000 men (1798), conquered the Spanish half of the island (1801), and effectively governed Saint-Domingue as an autonomous state.\n\nNapoleon Bonaparte, who had come to power in France and wished to restore slavery in the Caribbean colonies, sent his brother-in-law Charles Leclerc with 40,000 troops to reconquer Saint-Domingue in 1802. Leclerc captured Toussaint through treachery — luring him to a meeting under a flag of truce and arresting him. Toussaint was deported to France, where he died of pneumonia and neglect in a freezing mountain prison in April 1803, reportedly declaring, 'In overthrowing me, you have done no more than cut down the trunk of the tree of Black liberty in Saint-Domingue. It will spring back from the roots, for they are numerous and deep.'\n\nHis prophecy proved accurate. Jean-Jacques Dessalines, Toussaint's most aggressive lieutenant, continued the fight. Yellow fever devastated the French army — Leclerc himself died of it — and the resumption of war between France and Britain cut off reinforcements. At the Battle of Vertières on November 18, 1803, Dessalines's forces decisively defeated the remaining French troops. On January 1, 1804, Dessalines proclaimed the independence of Haiti (adopting the indigenous Taíno name for the island).\n\nThe Haitian Revolution's global impact was immense. It proved that enslaved people could achieve their own liberation through armed struggle, terrifying slaveholders throughout the Americas. Napoleon, having lost Saint-Domingue, sold the Louisiana Territory to the United States in 1803, doubling the young nation's size. The revolution inspired slave revolts and abolitionist movements worldwide, though Haiti itself was punished by international isolation: France demanded 150 million francs in 'compensation' for lost slave property (a debt not fully repaid until 1947), and the United States refused to recognize Haitian independence until 1862.",
